To address the request, we'll create a TikZ diagram that visually represents the linear realizations for the given sets. Each element group will be depicted as a colored node with exponent notation, arranged horizontally and connected sequentially.
```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=3mm]{standalone}
\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    node distance=1.5cm,
    element/.style={draw, circle, minimum size=8mm},
    label/.style={above, midway, font=\footnotesize}
]
% First linear realization: {1^6, 7^18}
\node[element, blue, fill=blue!10] (1a) at (0,0) {$1^6$};
\node[element, red, fill=red!10, right=of 1a] (7a) {$7^{18}$};
\draw[->, thick] (1a) -- (7a) node[label] {Transition};
% Second linear realization: {1^7, 7^17, 8^3}
\node[element, blue, fill=blue!10] (1b) at (0,-1.5) {$1^7$};
\node[element, red, fill=red!10, right=of 1b] (7b) {$7^{17}$};
\node[element, green!70!black, fill=green!10, right=of 7b] (8b) {$8^3$};
\draw[->, thick] (1b) -- (7b) node[label] {Transition};
\draw[->, thick] (7b) -- (8b) node[label] {Transition};
% Annotations
\node[align=center, font=\small] at (4,0) {First Realization:\\$\{1^6, 7^{18}\}$};
\node[align=center, font=\small] at (4,-1.5) {Second Realization:\\$\{1^7, 7^{17}, 8^3\}$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```
